The program is producing incorrect output because it's not updating `lastMa
`lastMatch` correctly. We need to update `lastMatch` only when we find a ma
matching item and this needs to be done outside of the if-statement since o
otherwise, even non-matching items would cause the last match value in `las
`lastMatch` to be updated.

So, here is the corrected program:

```tundra
val items = [
  { id: 4, matched: true },
  { id: 5, matched: false },
  { id: 7, matched: true }
];

var lastMatch = "none";
for(item in items) {
  if(item.matched) {
    print(item.id);
    lastMatch = item.id; // Update last match here outside the if-statement
if-statement
  }
}

print(lastMatch);
```
This program will output:
4
7
7
The loop first prints `4` and then `7` because it finds that the items with
with ids `4` and `7` are matching. The last print statement at the end outp
outputs the value of `lastMatch`, which is updated to be the id of the last
last matched item in the list i.e., `7`.
